@NODE "Using" "How To Write AG - Using This Project (BS)"
@TOC "AGHTW_Index/Main"

@{B}@{U}@{JCENTER}HOW TO WRITE AMIGAGUIDE DOCUMENTS

USING THIS PROJECT@{UB}@{UU}
@{JLEFT}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
I have included an icon with this archive which operates a @{"script" LINK "How_To_Write_Amigaguide/Main"} that
detects if you are using Amigaguide or Multiview. It has its default tool
set to "IconX". By this means I can overcome the problem of not knowing
which program (Amigaguide or Multiview) your Amiga has.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
I have set up the @{"CONTENTS button" LINK "AGHTW_Part3/Toc"} at the top of the display window to take
you to:-

- The @{"MAIN menu" LINK "AGHTW_Index/Main"} from nodes accessible from that menu,

- The @{"CONTENTS menu" LINK "AGHTW_Index/Contents"} from nodes accessible from that menu.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
While writing this project, I have used a viewing window that displays 42
lines of text. I mention this as there is a @{"problem" LINK "AGHTW_Part5/Problems"52} with Amigaguide and
Multiview when links jump to lines in a node other than the first line.

If you find that jumps to such links do not seem to get you where you
thought that they should, then check the size of your window. It would be
best to use one that has at least 75 characters of text across and not more
than 42 lines downwards. The more lines visible the more likely you are to
end up at a wrong line! Less lines than 42 should NOT cause a problem.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
As not all people use the same versions of Amigaguide or Multiview, I
cannot rely on the Amigaguide command @{"WORDWRAP" LINK "AGHTW_Part3/WordWrap"} or @{"SMARTWRAP" LINK "AGHTW_Part3/SmartWrap"} to properly
word wrap paragraphs. (These commands only work with amigaguide.library &
amigaguide.datatype version 39 and version 40 respectively.)

I have therefore formatted the articles so that each line that appears
in the window has a maximum of 76 characters with a @{"line feed" LINK "AGHTW_Part5/LineFeed"} at the end
of each line rather than only at the end of each paragraph. This should
allow each line to be displayed in a window that has the same width as your
screen provided that you are not using a font size bigger than 8.

But if lines are extending beyond the right edge of the window when reading
this article you may have to do one or more of:-

- widen the window to the full width of the screen

- reset your screen preferences to a width of 255 pixels at least

- reset the "Fonts" preferences to set the "System Default Text" font
  to a size of 8 or less.

If you are using the standard preferences that came with your Amiga then
you should not have any problems.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The text in this project has been formatted with some text:-

@{B}In bold text@{UB}

@{U}With underlined text@{UU}

@{JCENTER}Centred text
@{JLEFT}
If the above three lines are @{B}NOT@{UB}, respectively, in bold underlined
and centred, then you have an early version of the Amigaguide/Multiview.

Bold and underlining is available from version 39 onwards (AmigaDOS v3.0).

Centring is available from version 40 onwards (AmigaDOS v3.1).

If you have an Amigaguide/Multiview version earlier than 40 then the
formatting will not be as good as it could be. However, I trust that this
will not prevent you from getting the full benefit of the project.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you notice that, in some articles, there is a gap between the line
"=== End of Text ===" and the end of the window then @{B}DO NOT@{UB} go into the
file and delete these blank lines!! They are there because some instances of
cross referencing can be to some of the last lines of a node. If the blank
lines were not there then the cross reference link would go to a line before
the intended line.

@{B}This is a@{UB} @{"fault with Multiview/Amigaguide" LINK "AGHTW_Part5/Problems"52}@{B} not with my editing!@{UB}

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you are using version 39 then you may find that clicking on a link
button then clicking on the "Retrace" button does NOT take you back to your
previous place in the project. This happens if the link button references a
place in the @{B}SAME NODE@{UB} as the one being viewed.

For example, @{"this button" LINK "Using"20} should take you to a spot further up in this node
to a line starting with:-

  While writing this project ......   - version 34
  The line with ~~~~~~ above it       - version 39/40

If, after clicking the button, you then click on the "Retrace" button:-

  With Version 39      - you will be taken back to the point you were at
                         before before reaching this node.
  With Version 34 & 40 - you will be returned here.

I am afraid that I cannot think of any way to overcome this problem. It
seems to be a fault with the version 39 that was not in v34 and that has
been corrected in version 40.

This problem is @{"one reason" LINK "History"24} why I split a lot of the project into smaller
nodes.


~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{JCENTER}=== End of Text ===







































